 
This is a message from a dying civilisation. 

Can you even read this? Is there a guidebook on human languages and how they work included in this archive?

I'm Mateo – I’m 25 years old. I live in Amsterdam, the Netherlands. I’m an art student and filmmaker/visual artist – or at least trying to be one. I’m writing in English because it’s kind of considered a ‘universal' language in our society but there are many other languages too. Many ways to communicate. Many ways to connect to each other, to collaborate, to help, but also to hurt, alienate, dehumanise and deny solidarity to others, whether it is with other humans or with other lifeforms in our ecosystem.

Now it feels like a time where things are falling apart. I always grew up with this idea that we were all, in however minuscule ways, contributing to this huge project of ‘human civilisation’. Part of me still believes in that project somehow, that somehow people will remember me, my work and ideas, or maybe just my genes getting passed on. 

But now we don’t really know anymore. Our leaders don’t have the will to stand up against the profit of a small elite in order to prevent a catastrophic breakdown of our climate systems and the way they facilitates life on our planet. The majority of us are kept ignorant or in denial and we don’t seem anywhere close to cause the political revolution that we need in order to actually save our existence as we know it. Paradoxically, the rich people and private companies funding this archive are probably also part of the whole problem in the first place.

Maybe the way some of us deal with the knowledge of our mortality is to convince ourselves of the immortality of a greater kind of self:, our human culture.

But what I am here for then, if this ‘human civilisation’ project is coming to an end?

Maybe you’re already familiar with all of this. Maybe you have access to a bunch of different human's accounts. Maybe you’re an expert archeologist from an alien race, digging through the remains of the last part of the anthropocene. Maybe it’s more interesting to talk about less rational things. Things more unique to me but maybe somehow also more universally human (this is the kind of thing that some people try to teach you if pursue a career in art).

About four years ago I made a little book for someone that I was in love with. I wrote down something like:

"One day, the world will shatter into a billion tiny pieces and one of those pieces will be a fragment of this paper, that shows, not proves, that we created something as real as something could be”.

I’m really happy to still be in love with that person. And perhaps in a bittersweet kind of way, I’m really happy that I still believe in what I wrote. I think that's why I’m here, writing into this near-certain void. Somewhere I still believe that we’re somehow eternal, even if all that’s left is a particle of bone dust flying through space. Somehow I believe that our moments of love and joy are deeply meaningful and inextricably tied with the fate of the universe – however fleeting and small they may be. Is this a very hopeful thought? I think it’s also a very human thought.

Humans are incredibly hopeful creatures. Maybe that’s going to be our downfall, that too many of us stayed hopeful about the way we were taught things are supposed to work when it was clearly destroying so much of what we love, when it was cancelling so many better, fairer futures that never ended up happening.


This is a poem in Spanish and Dutch I wrote for a film I’m working on. It was a way of coming to terms with how my real, mortal, physical self was never going to live up to the idealised imaged I had constructed of myself. But in the film I also loosely related it to lost futures in general, especially in a time of political uncertainty.

Perhaps it will give you some kind of insight on how one particular human chose to express themselves.

’there is a ghost of me / er is een geest van mij’

SOMEWHERE
IN LIMA
WHERE HISTORIC HOUSES ARE SET ON FIRE
SOMEWHERE
IN NY & DC
AFTER THE 2016 PRESIDENTIAL ELECTION
SOMEWHERE
IN AMSTERDAM
WHERE ABANDONED HOUSES WHISPER ABOUT THE PAST
SOMWHERE
IN MY HEAD
GUTS
